Ian, thanks for the info. It seems that this is not directly related to cookies, but to the fact that disabling cookies also disables sessionStorage. 

I can confirm that a web page with the following code will trigger the errors, if cookies are disabled:

> <!DOCTYPE html>
> <meta charset="UTF-8"> 
> <html>
> <body onload="storeSessionStuff()">
> <p>I'm in ur session, storing ur stuff...</p>
> <p id="urParagraph">Trying...</p>
> <script>
> function storeSessionStuff() {
> 	try {
>    		sessionStorage.setItem("urStuff","I stored some stuff!");
>   		document.getElementById("urParagraph").innerHTML = sessionStorage.getItem("urStuff");
> 	} catch(err) {
> 		document.getElementById("urParagraph").innerHTML = "Computer says no. " + err.message;
> 	}
> }
> </script>
> </body>
> </html>

Note that it's only necessary to read and/or write sessionStorage, not set cookies.

Loading this page will reproduce all the above history errors consistently, in Firefox 43.0-46.0a1, even when opened from the New Tab page. It generates the error "The operation is insecure" which is caught by the script, but also causes the same error from SessionStorage.jsm, after which the history operations fail.

On the other hand, if the same sessionStorage function is triggered by clicking a button, rather than loading the page, the same error is generated and caught by the script, but the SessionStorage.jsm error doesn't happen, and the page history and restore works normally. Go figure.

> <!DOCTYPE html>
> <meta charset="UTF-8"> 
> <html>
> <body>
> <p>I'm in ur session, storing ur stuff...</p>
> <button type="button" onclick="storeSessionStuff()">button</button>
> <p id="urParagraph">^^ Click this.</p>
> <script>
> function storeSessionStuff() {
> 	try {
>    		sessionStorage.setItem("urStuff","I stored some stuff!");
>   		document.getElementById("urParagraph").innerHTML = sessionStorage.getItem("urStuff");
> 	} catch(err) {
> 		document.getElementById("urParagraph").innerHTML = "Computer says no. " + err.message;
> 	}
> }
> </script>
> </body>
> </html>

Dao, I'm hoping you can shed some light here. The issue is that using the DevEdition theme, a toolbarbutton in a panel UI, with no explicit color rule, is showing up with white text when the button is anywhere other than the toolbar, and black text when it is in the toolbar.

The reason is the rule at https://dxr.mozilla.org/mozilla-central/rev/6764bc656c1d146962d53710d734c2ac87c2306f/browser/themes/osx/browser.css#73:

> #navigator-toolbox toolbarbutton:-moz-lwtheme {
>  color: inherit;
>  text-shadow: inherit;
> }

So only when the panel button is in the toolbar, and only on OSX, the color is inherited from the window, which has specified black.

I know it's a long time ago, but best I can tell, this was added in bug 511107.

I'm guessing the rule is supposed to apply for buttons directly in the toolbox rather than for buttons in a panel opened from the button (ie, that the rule should be |#navigator-toolbox > toolbarbutton:-moz-lwtheme|)? Or maybe just specifying white in the style for the button is the appropriate fix? Or something else I'm missing?

FTR, the button in question is https://dxr.mozilla.org/mozilla-central/rev/6764bc656c1d146962d53710d734c2ac87c2306f/browser/components/customizableui/content/panelUI.inc.xul#136

