https://reviewboard.mozilla.org/r/43297/#review40941

About the rAF: is there in order to ensure that react components have time to render themselves. Specifically, as you indicates in your previous review we have to hide the handle that resize the viewport. Since the handler itself become invisible if `screenshot.isCapturing` is `true`, we need to wait the next repaint.
That's the only way I thought it could be done in a "react way", but if you know a better approach let me know! As alternative, we can always doing it old-school (setting an attribute on the document.body for example, or to the viewport's node, inside the action).

About Helen's comment: So, yeah, when I saw the comment I was confused, because it seems to me that was the opposite of what she said during the stand up, so I contacted her and she confirmed she changed her mind in the meantime. :) I'll explain better below.

> Why do you need rAF here?

As explained above, is there in order to ensure that react components have time to render themselves; otherwise the handle won't be hidden when the snapshot is taken.

> Given Helen's comment 42 (read carefully, it's different from what was discussed at the standup), it seems `simulatedCameraEffects` should happen pretty early (Helen says "on press"), so maybe just after:
> 
>   yield dispatch({type: TAKE_SCREENSHOT_START});

Yes, it's different from what she said before. I think it's safe having the `simulatedCameraEffects` here; I put there because everything is used in the same scope, otherwise I have to do something like:
```js
    return function* (dispatch, getState) {
      yield dispatch({ type: TAKE_SCREENSHOT_START });

      let iframe = document.querySelector("iframe");
      simulateCameraEffects(iframe);

      window.requestAnimationFrame(async(function* () {
        let data = createScreenshotFor(iframe);

        yield saveToFile(data, getFileName());

        dispatch({ type: TAKE_SCREENSHOT_END });
      }));
    };

```
I think is cleaner and readable as is, but if you prefer the code above I don't have strong opinion about that. Let me know!

> In Helen's comment 37, she requested `cursor: pointer` for all buttons.

She asked if it's possible; and yes, it's possible but I didn't change that because I think we should discuss this topic, despite this bug.
I'm saying that because currently I'm not aware of any of our UI that uses `pointer` for buttons in devtools or Firefox, so we won't be consistent with our UI, that I think is important. Maybe there is a bug about changing them to `pointer` for all our buttons?

